-- U.S. Stocks Gain After Jump in Holiday Retail Sales; GM Rises
-- B y   R i t a   N a z a r e t h
-- 2010-12-28T14:37:02Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-28/stock-index-futures-rise-before-economic-reports-gm-exxon-gain-in-europe.html
U.S. stocks advanced, with the
Standard & Poor’s 500 Index extending the biggest December rally
since 1991, as a report showed the best holiday sales for
retailers in five years.  Target Corp.  and Abercrombie & Fitch Co. rallied at least
0.4 percent after MasterCard Advisors’ SpendingPulse said
Christmas retail sales, excluding autos, jumped 5.5 percent.
 Freeport-McMoRan Copper & Gold Inc.  added 0.2 percent as copper
advanced to a record.  General Motors Co.  rose 2.4 percent as at
least seven firms, including JPMorgan Chase & Co. and Morgan
Stanley, initiated coverage of the automaker with a positive
view.  The  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  rose 0.1 percent to
1,259.31 at 9:35 a.m. in New York. The  Dow Jones Industrial
Average  advanced 17.86 points, or 0.2 percent, to 11,572.89.  “People got tired of putting money in their pockets,”
said  Walter Todd , who helps manage about $900 million at
Greenwood Capital Associates in Greenwood, South Carolina.
“There’s been a fair amount of consumer demand. That’s a very
positive indication of an economic recovery and signals a pretty
decent upcoming year for stocks.”  The S&P 500 rose for the sixth day in seven yesterday,
reversing losses of as much as 0.4 percent from earlier in the
session as American International Group Inc. led financial
shares higher after announcing $4.3 billion in bank credit
lines. The benchmark gauge, which is up 13 percent this year and
6.5 percent this month through yesterday, is heading for the
biggest December rally since 1991.  Home Prices  Home prices dropped more than forecast in October, a sign
housing will remain a weak link as the U.S. recovery accelerates
into the new year. The S&P/Case-Shiller index of property values
fell 0.8 percent from October 2009, the biggest year-over-year
decline since December 2009, the group said today. The decrease
exceeded the 0.2 percent drop projected by the median forecast
of economists surveyed by Bloomberg News.  A report today may show consumer confidence rose to a
seven-month high in December. The Conference Board’s confidence
index increased to 56.3 this month from 54.1 in November,
according to the median estimate of economists surveyed.  Retail sales, excluding autos, rose to $584 billion from
Nov. 5 through Dec. 24, said MasterCard Advisors’ SpendingPulse,
which measures retail sales by all payment forms. That compared
with a 4.1 percent gain a year earlier. The numbers include
sales made over the Web.  Target, Abercrombie  Target, rallied 0.4 percent to $60.27. Abercrombie rose 0.5
percent to $57.42.  Raw materials producers rallied following a rebound in
commodities prices. Copper gained to a record in New York for a
second day as investors sought alternatives to depreciating
currencies and on expectation demand will outpace supply as
consumption improves.  Freeport, the largest publicly traded copper producer,
gained 0.2 percent to $118.82. Newmont Mining Corp. added 1.7
percent to $61.08.  General Motors  advanced 2.4 percent to $35.44. JPMorgan,
Morgan Stanley, RBC Capital, Citigroup Inc., Bank of America
Corp., Barclays Plc, Credit Suisse Group AG recommended the
automaker’s stocks.  “GM has the chance to translate competitive costs and a
strong balance sheet into something it hasn’t been able to do in
50 years,”  Adam Jonas , an London-based analyst at Morgan
Stanley, wrote in a note today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Rita Nazareth  in Sao Paulo at 
 rnazareth@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net . 